[4] Shigellosis - China (Hong Kong SAR)
Date: Mon 18 Jun 2012
Source: 7th Space, Hong Kong Government report [edited]
http://7thspace.com/headlines/414964/more_bacillary_dysentery_cases_in_tuen_mun.html


The Centre for Health Protection (CHP) of the Department of Health investigated 3 more cases of bacillary dysentery infection upon receipt of notification from Tuen Mun Hospital (TMH) today, 18 Jun 2012.

The cases involved 3 females aged between 3 and 29. They developed symptoms of fever, diarrhea, and vomiting from 10 Jun 2012 to 12 Jun 2012. All of them consulted the Accident and Emergency Department of TMH and did not require hospitalization. The patients all lived in Tuen Mun.

Preliminary investigation revealed that their stool specimens all grew _Shigella sonnei_.

The investigation is continuing. The notification brings the cumulative number of bacillary dysentery cases to 9 in June 2012 so far.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Tuen Mun is a town near the mouth of Tuen Mun River and Castle Peak Bay in the New Territories, Hong Kong. It can be located on the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map at http://healthmap.org/r/2BYA. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]

******
[5] Cholera - China
Date: Tue 12 Jun 2012
Source: Xinhua News Agency [edited]
http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/china/2012-06/12/c_131648374.htm


More than 982 932 cases of infectious diseases were reported on the Chinese mainland in May 2012, resulting in 1575 deaths, the Ministry of Health said Tue 12 Jun 2012.

7 cases of cholera, a Category A infectious disease, were reported, but none were fatal, according to the statement.

